  "text": "a phase-shifted (n\u22121)-dimensional harmonic (Fig. 3(c) , red curve), where proj \u03a0 \u03c9 is the perpendicular projection of \u03c9 onto \u03a0, and the phase shift 2\u03c0dn \u00b7 \u03c9 depends on both the distance from \u03a0 to the origin and the relative orientation of n and \u03c9. Note that proj \u03a0 \u03c9 is the component of \u03c9 parallel to \u03a0, and n \u00b7 \u03c9 is the length of the component of \u03c9 perpendicular to \u03a0. We now observe that, because of the phase shift ( Fig. 3(a,c) , \u03c6 s ), the product of the sliced Gaussian (Eqn. 3) and the sliced harmonic (Eqn. 4) cannot be expressed as a Gabor kernel (Eqn. 1). In other words, the Gabor kernel of [CITATION_1] is not closed under slicing.",
